{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"df92fa9a-27c5-4137-b222-14a92bbf4f67","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is exactly what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions required by a new SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK changed → versions need to catch up → use `update`. If workloads were already the right version but files were corrupted, that's when you'd use `repair`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf it still fails afterward, try a clean restore:\n\n```bash\ndotnet clean && dotnet restore\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7504cc78-f9c2-4392-8413-cd23fd5826f0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":267,"requestId":"DBC5:127F79:7987B:99FDB:69F549F0"},"id":"dcd6c321-2658-40f7-a9fc-781c156fd765","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:48:56.251Z","parentId":"005cf966-6538-4812-95de-92866a349d85"}
